  "prompt": "How long do antibiotics stay in the system after discontinuation?",
  "response": "The time antibiotics remain in the system varies depending on several factors:\n\n1. Specific antibiotic type\n- Short-acting: 24-48 hours\n- Medium-acting: 3-5 days\n- Long-acting: Up to 10-14 days\n\n2. Factors affecting elimination:\n- Individual metabolism\n- Kidney and liver function\n- Age\n- Dosage\n- Overall health\n\n3. General elimination timelines:\n- Most antibiotics are cleared within 48-72 hours\n- Some traces may remain in bloodstream for up to a week\n- Complete system clearance typically occurs within 7-10 days\n\n4. Specific antibiotic examples:\n- Amoxicillin: 1-2 days\n- Azithromycin: 5-7 days\n- Ciprofloxacin: 3-4 days\n\n5. Potential lingering effects:\n- Side effects may persist briefly after medication stops\n- Gut microbiome recovery can take weeks to months\n\nNote: Always consult healthcare professionals for personalized medical advice regarding specific antibiotic use and elimination.",
